• Over here taking care of business...it was abundantly clear that the living room needed a good cleaning because of all the, you know, living that goes on in there. It was...bad. 

I stripped the rugs and sofa covers and discovered a few lost, erm, treasures. But you know the best thing about sofa covers? A quick and easy clean to feel like a brand new couch again. Look for a blog post later this week all about how I care for our couch covers and a few of my top picks from @comfortworks 

I may have asked the kids to keep snacks away for now but how long do you think that lasted? Ah, well 🤷‍♀️😂

Middle school was a particularly rough time for me for many reasons (I mean, does anyone really *enjoy* middle school?). I went through an ugly duckling phase (that I never really grew out of, mentally) and felt mostly out of place - like a missing puzzle piece swept beneath the rug - lost and unable to fit. 

Do you remember your middle school crushes? I remember having crushes and feeling as if no one liked me  back - and I wondered if anyone would ever like *me*. It was a lonely feeling - especially as I was navigating what it meant when I was crushing on both boys and girls. 

I knew what *being gay* meant - and the message that I picked up from the peers around me was that it was disgusting and shameful.  I specifically remember internally wondering, asking, even pleading with myself, “how will I know? How will I know if I’m gay or straight?” It was terrifying, in a way, because I *came to age* during a time when Pride didn’t exist in the way it does today and when ‘gay, fag, dyke’ were routinely tossed about as slurs in the hallways, every day. It made me feel broken - like I hadn’t been put together correctly - and I definitely wouldn’t be telling anyone about it, ever. Honestly, it wasn’t until I was in college that I truly understood that bisexuality was an actual thing. Who’d. Have. Thunk?! 

Figuring out who you are and accepting yourself can be incredibly hard - especially as a youth. I combatted my awkwardness with clownish humor - always trying to mask how odd I felt (and I became pretty fucking great at masking). I could pretend to be anything - anyone - just to shrug off the person who I was afraid to be. 

I suppose that’s what Pride is all about - being able to embrace, accept, and celebrate yourself without fear of being ostracized, rejected, hated, harmed, bullied, belittled, or killed. 

The reality is that LGBTQ+ youth are four times more likely to attempt suicide, according to The Trevor Project. More than half of transgender or nonbinary youth have considered attempting suicide in the past year. Don’t underestimate the value of a Pride flag, affirmation, and supportive groups - they save lives - they make an impact.

** Enchanted cottage, anyone? **

I always work to create outdoor spaces that will encourage our kids to let their imaginations run wild. We’ve been working on so many of these spots but this one is almost too much. We nabbed this Frozen playhouse for Molly’s birthday and the amount of detail and whimsy is off the charts! I’m considering moving in….and am also convinced there are mystical fairies flitting about, now. We found the perfect little nook to nestle this cottage and it truly feels like it’s within an enchanted forest.

I’ll share more details up on the blog, later. Until then, you can find this playhouse on my Amazon storefront - browse my collection anytime by following the link in my bio. I’ll also link it up in stories, tonight!

• My nightly routine almost always involves hand washing the dishes I can’t fit in the dishwasher, diffusing some oils, and pouring a splash of wine. 

Anyway, tonight I opened my new pack of dishcloths and oils from @folkulture and they made me just a little more excited about scrubbing down the remnants of burrito bowls. 

I’ve had a blast working with @folkulture for the past several years and genuinely love their stuff! I’m ordering another set of these dishcloths with a matching set of hand towels. As for the oils? They are light and refreshing without being overwhelming - a solid match for those sensitive to strong scents. 

As always, I’ll link these picks in stories - you can visit my Folkulture collection on my Amazon storefront anytime through the link in my bio and on the blog. I’ll just call this a night of scrub, sniff, and  sip. Ha. Haha.

Take this kiss upon the brow!

And, in parting from you now,

Thus much let me avow —

You are not wrong, who deem

That my days have been a dream;

Yet if hope has flown away

In a night, or in a day,

In a vision, or in none,

Is it therefore the less gone? 

All that we see or seem

Is but a dream within a dream.

I stand amid the roar

Of a surf-tormented shore,

And I hold within my hand

Grains of the golden sand —

How few! yet how they creep

Through my fingers to the deep,

While I weep — while I weep!

O God! Can I not grasp

Them with a tighter clasp?

O God! can I not save

One from the pitiless wave?

Is all that we see or seem

But a dream within a dream?

•Edgar Allan Poe•

Looking down this long, dark hallway always gives me pause - especially during the holidays. There’s something so ethereal about the glow of candlelight flicker bouncing off the old glass frames covering the walls. The halls have been decked with thick strands of cedar garlands donned with burgundy bows hidden in the shadows of the rafters. It’s both comforting and unsettling, in a way. Like I’m being pulled in, somehow grasped by the warmth while feeling an undercurrent of uncertainty waiting in the darkness. 

What I’ve come to understand about this season is that there is a pull between joy and sorrow - there is happiness, light, and merriment right alongside grief, despair, and unimaginable heartache. That sometimes, we feel the pressure to embrace this as the ‘most wonderful time of the year’ when our bodies, minds, and souls are simply drained. 

It’s almost like there’s a culmination of all of the joys and sorrows the past year has brought intermixed with the hopes and anxieties for the new year ahead. Honestly, all of those feelings can be fucking hard to navigate. While there are days or moments when we might feel energized and filled with comfort - there are also moments when we are weary - our holiday spirit having been completely spent - hollowing us out. 

I struggle with this - and I want you to know that there’s no pressure to feel a certain way right now (or anytime of the year). It’s okay to feel waves of conflicting emotions - you’re not a grinch if your heart is so big that it carries the weight of mountains of sorrow and pain and you’re not selfish if you set aside obligations to do something that gives you joy. No one is allowed to tell you how to feel, how to be, and how to live out this season. And if you’re feeling undone and a bit unraveled, you’re not alone. There are many of us sitting alongside you - know that I am manifesting peace to you, my friends.

I stumbled across an old journal of mine. I thought I had thrown them all away (I don’t particularly enjoy reliving - but sometimes, I’m reminded that looking to the past can reveal growth or even strengthen your sense of self). 

I had recently graduated high school and was preparing to move from Colorado to Iowa. My last entry in this journal was June 10th, the day we left. I wrote this entry on June 9, 2005:

“I am about to leave for the flat lands of emptiness. While the trees and lakes of Iowa can be beautiful, my thoughts are clouded within a wild storm of loneliness. I want so much to be happy there but my smile is fading and my dreams have given way…knowing that my heart lies elsewhere. My heart remains hidden in the quiet, looming mountains of my home in Colorado. Its whispers can be heard only by the rain, the snow, and the ghost of my footprints.” Wow - look at me all angsty and such 😅

I’ve always told myself I can find happiness and beauty anywhere - and I have. But there’s something to say about finding/discovering your roots within the Earth. It’s good to know that the pull I’ve felt all these years was not in vain. I’ve realized that I’m so fortunate to be able to return to that piece of myself that I left behind - that I’ve branched to many places and connected with people that have helped me grow - that I’ve been able to reconnect with places and people dear to me - and that I’ve always been rather melancholic and pensive in my writing. 🫣

Enjoy a few of the quick captures of these beautiful Rocky Mountain moments from the end of 2023. I’m thankful to share this journey and my captures with you.

Chicken Francese 🙌 It was great though the kids gave it a lackluster review (don't listen to them, they don't know what they're talking about). Ingredients: 1/2 cup plus 1 tablespoon all-purpose flour, divided
1 1/2 teaspoons kosher salt, divided
1/2 teaspoon black pepper
2 large eggs
2 tablespoons water
1/4 cup canola or vegetable oil
4 boneless, skinless chicken breast cutlets (about 1 pound total)
1/2 large lemon, sliced into rounds
1 cup chicken broth
1/2 cup dry white wine
Juice 1/2 large lemon
2 tablespoons butter
2 tablespoons fresh parsley leaves. Do the thing: Place 1/2 cup of the flour, 1 teaspoon of the salt, and the pepper in a wide, shallow bowl and whisk to combine. Whisk the eggs and water together in a separate bowl.
Heat the oil over medium-high heat until simmering. Cover the chicken in the flour.
Coat the chicken with the egg mixture. Cook until lightly browned, about 3 minutes per side. Transfer the chicken to a paper towel-lined plate. 
Discard the oil in the skillet. Add the lemon slices to the skillet and cook about 30 seconds. Add the wine, broth, lemon juice, and remaining 1/2 teaspoon of salt. Simmer about 5 minutes. Combine the remaining 1 tablespoon of flour into the butter in a small bowl to make a paste.
Add the paste to the sauce and whisk until melted. Put the chicken back in the pan and cook until the sauce is thickened and the chicken is heated through. Garnish with the parsley before diggin' in! Recipe credit: @thekitchn
